# React (Web) to Expo React Native Conversion Guide

## Overview

This guide covers converting a React web application to a **React Native app using Expo**. React Native uses the same JavaScript/TypeScript and component model as React, but instead of rendering HTML to a browser, it renders **native mobile UI components** (iOS & Android). Many React concepts map directly, but the rendering layer, styling, navigation, and platform APIs are completely different.

## Tech Stack

- **Expo**: SDK 55+ (managed workflow)
- **React Native**: 0.83+ (via Expo, New Architecture required)
- **Expo Router**: v4.x (file-based navigation — replaces React Router)
- **React**: 19.x
- **TypeScript**: 5.x
- **NativeWind**: v4.x (Tailwind-style classes for React Native, optional)

> **SDK 55 breaking change**: Legacy Architecture support has been dropped. All apps must use React Native's New Architecture. The `newArchEnabled` config option no longer exists in `app.json`.

---

## Core Mental Shift

| React Web | React Native (Expo) |
|-----------|---------------------|
| Renders HTML elements (`div`, `p`, `button`, `input`) | Renders native components (`View`, `Text`, `Pressable`, `TextInput`) |
| CSS / Tailwind for styling | `StyleSheet.create()` or NativeWind |
| `className="..."` | `style={styles.xxx}` or NativeWind `className` |
| Browser routing (URL bar) | Stack/tab navigation (no URL bar on mobile) |
| `React Router` / `Next.js` | `Expo Router` (file-based) |
| `window`, `document` | Not available — use Expo APIs |
| `localStorage` | `AsyncStorage` / `expo-secure-store` |
| `fetch()` / Axios | Same — works in React Native |
| `onClick` | `onPress` |
| Scrollable by default | Must use `ScrollView` or `FlatList` explicitly |
| CSS `display: flex` (horizontal default) | `View` is `flexDirection: 'column'` by default |

> React Native's `View` uses **Flexbox** but defaults to **column direction**, not row like CSS.

