## Styling

### CSS / Tailwind → StyleSheet.create()

React Native has **no CSS**. Styles are JavaScript objects.

| CSS / Tailwind | React Native StyleSheet |
|----------------|------------------------|
| `display: flex` | default (no need to declare) |
| `flex-direction: row` | `flexDirection: 'row'` |
| `align-items: center` | `alignItems: 'center'` |
| `justify-content: space-between` | `justifyContent: 'space-between'` |
| `padding: 16px` | `padding: 16` (numbers, not strings) |
| `border-radius: 8px` | `borderRadius: 8` |
| `font-size: 16px` | `fontSize: 16` |
| `color: #333` | `color: '#333'` |
| `background-color: blue` | `backgroundColor: 'blue'` |
| `width: 100%` | `width: '100%'` (strings for %) |
| `margin-top: 8px` | `marginTop: 8` |
| `box-shadow` | `shadow*` props (iOS) + `elevation` (Android) |
| `overflow: hidden` | `overflow: 'hidden'` |

```tsx
const styles = StyleSheet.create({
    container: {
        flex: 1,
        backgroundColor: '#fff',
        padding: 16,
    },
    row: {
        flexDirection: 'row',
        alignItems: 'center',
        justifyContent: 'space-between',
    },
    title: {
        fontSize: 24,
        fontWeight: 'bold',
        color: '#111827',
    },
});
```

### NativeWind (Optional — Tailwind classes in React Native)

If you prefer Tailwind syntax, install NativeWind:

```tsx
// With NativeWind installed, use className like web React
<View className="flex-1 bg-white p-4">
    <Text className="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900">Title</Text>
</View>
```

