## Navigation

### React Router → Expo Router (File-Based)

Expo Router uses the `app/` folder — the file path becomes the route, just like Next.js.

| React Router | Expo Router |
|--------------|-------------|
| `<Route path="/" element={<Home />} />` | `app/index.tsx` |
| `<Route path="/products" element={<Products />} />` | `app/products/index.tsx` |
| `<Route path="/products/:id" element={<Show />} />` | `app/products/[id].tsx` |
| `<Link to="/products">` | `<Link href="/products">` from `expo-router` |
| `useNavigate()` | `useRouter()` from `expo-router` |
| `useParams()` | `useLocalSearchParams()` from `expo-router` |

### Navigation in Code

```tsx
// React Web
import { useNavigate, useParams } from 'react-router-dom';
const navigate = useNavigate();
navigate('/products');
const { id } = useParams();

// React Native (Expo Router)
import { useRouter, useLocalSearchParams, Link } from 'expo-router';
const router = useRouter();
router.push('/products');
router.back();
const { id } = useLocalSearchParams<{ id: string }>();
```

### Stack Navigation Layout

```tsx
// app/_layout.tsx
import { Stack } from 'expo-router';

export default function RootLayout() {
    return (
        <Stack>
            <Stack.Screen name="index" options={{ title: 'Home' }} />
            <Stack.Screen name="products/index" options={{ title: 'Products' }} />
            <Stack.Screen name="products/[id]" options={{ title: 'Product Detail' }} />
        </Stack>
    );
}
```

### Tab Navigation

```tsx
// app/(tabs)/_layout.tsx
import { Tabs } from 'expo-router';

export default function TabLayout() {
    return (
        <Tabs>
            <Tabs.Screen name="index" options={{ title: 'Home', tabBarIcon: ... }} />
            <Tabs.Screen name="products" options={{ title: 'Products' }} />
            <Tabs.Screen name="profile" options={{ title: 'Profile' }} />
        </Tabs>
    );
}
```

